.12.22-AM.png 732w, https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-6.12.22-AM-300x210.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 732px) 100vw, 732px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>Fill in project name, organization name, identifier (like com.yourcompany) and for now, unchecking unit tests. I&#8217;m experimenting with a new Mightyverse prototype so I filled in:<br \/>\n* PhraseRecorder<br \/>\n* Mightyverse<br \/>\n* com.mightyverse<\/p>\n<p>which created the app identifier:  com.mightyverse.PhraseRecorder<\/p>\n<p>It will also create a folder full of files named with your project name and this will also be the name of the app.  I don&#8217;t like spaces in file paths, so I use camel case with no spaces.<\/p>\n<p>Run the app now and you should see a blank white screen.  I usually use iPhone 5 since the screen is small and easy to preview on my laptop. Let&#8217;s go to the home screen and see how the project name is used as the app name.  (Choose Hardware &gt; Home or shift-command-H)<\/p>\n<p><a class=\"thumbnail\" href=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.04.47-AM.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.04.47-AM.png\" alt=\"multiple icons on home screen, new app has truncated name followed by an elipsis\" width=\"320\" height=\"207\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-5772\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.04.47-AM.png 320w, https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.04.47-AM-300x194.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>The name I picked was too long so it appears truncated with elipses.  This wasn&#8217;t the name I wanted the end user to see anyhow.  This is easy to fix in XCode 7 (though not very discoverable).  Stop the app (using the VCR controls at the top of the XCode window). Then click the little folder icon to see your file listing, then double click on the target name in the middle panel and type a new name.<\/p>\n<p><a class=\"thumbnail\" href=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.07.33-AM.png\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.07.33-AM.png\" alt=\"First item selected in first panel, target in second\" width=\"509\" height=\"326\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-5773\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.07.33-AM.png 509w, https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/12\/Screen-Shot-2015-12-22-at-7.07.33-AM-300x192.png 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 509px) 100vw, 509px\" \/><\/a><\/p>\n<p>Run the app again and&#8230; voila! your app has a new name.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Create a new application (File &gt; New &gt; Project) Create a Single View Application as usual&#8230; Name your project: Fill in project name, organization name, identifier (like com.yourcompany) and for now, unchecking unit tests. I&#8217;m experimenting with a new Mightyverse prototype so I filled in: * PhraseRecorder * Mightyverse * com.mightyverse which created the app&hellip; <a href=\"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/2015\/12\/xcode-7-creating-and-renaming-a-new-app\/\">Continue reading <span class=\"meta-nav\">&rarr;<\/span><\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":84,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[2],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/5754"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.ultrasaurus.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"hre